            </Paragraph>

          </TableCell>

        </TableRow>

      </TableRowGroup>

    </Table>

    <Paragraph>This example shows how to use Trigger elements to style a CheckBox control.
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph FontSize="22">Example
    </Paragraph>

    <Paragraph>The following example creates a style that changes the appearance of a <Run FontWeight="Bold">CheckBox</Run>
 in response to events that are raised on the control. When you move the mouse pointer over the <Run FontWeight="Bold">CheckBox</Run>
, the Background color changes and if you select the <Run FontWeight="Bold">CheckBox</Run>
, the Foreground color changes.
    </Paragraph>

    <Table CellSpacing="5">
      <TableRowGroup>
        <TableRow>
          <TableCell>
            <Paragraph FontSize="22"><Run>XAML </Run>

            </Paragraph>

          </TableCell>

        </TableRow>

        <TableRow>
          <TableCell>
            <Paragraph xml:space="preserve" TextAlignment="Left" FontSize="8pt" FontFamily="Courier New"><Run>
&lt;Style x:Key="Triggers" TargetType="{x:Type CheckBox}"> 
&lt;Style.Triggers> 
&lt;Trigger Property="CheckBox.IsPressed" Value="true"> 
&lt;Setter Property = "Foreground" Value="Green"/> 
&lt;/Trigger> 
&lt;Trigger Property="CheckBox.IsMouseOver" Value="true"> 
&lt;Setter Property = "Background" Value="Red"/> 
&lt;/Trigger> 
&lt;/Style.Triggers> 
&lt;/Style> </Run>

            </Paragraph>

          </TableCell>

        </TableRow>

      </TableRowGroup>

    </Table>

    <Paragraph>For the complete sample, see CheckBox Styles Sample.
